Sometimes, I feel ashamed to be a European.
Last year, over a million people in need of our help arrived in Europe and our response was frankly pathetic.
There are so many contradictions.
We mourn the tragic death of Alan Kurdi, a two-year-old child, and yet, since then, over 200 children have drowned in the Mediterranean.
International treaties recognize that refugees are a shared responsibility, and yet we accept that little Lebanon hosts more Syrians than all of Europe combined.
We lament the existence of smugglers, yet we make them the only viable route for seeking asylum in Europe.
We are short of labor, and yet we prevent people who fit our economic and demographic needs from coming to Europe.
We proclaim our liberal values in opposition to fundamentalist Islam, yet -- we have enforcement policies that detain minor asylum seekers, separate children from their families, and seize the belongings of refugees.
What are we doing?
How did we get to the point where we adopt such an inhumane response to a humanitarian crisis?
I do not believe it is due to indifference, at least I do not want to believe that.
I believe it's because our politicians lack vision, they don't know how to adapt the international asylum rules, created over 50 years ago, to globalization.
I want to take a step back and ask two fundamental questions, the two questions that we must all ask.
Firstly, why doesn't the current system work?
Secondly, how can we remedy this?
The current system for refugees was created in response to the consequences of World War II by these people.
Its primary goal is to ensure that when a state fails, or worse, turns against its own people, there is a place for them to go, where they can live in safety and with dignity until they can return home.
It was specifically created for situations like the current one in Syria.
Through an international convention signed by 147 governments, the 1951 Refugee Status Convention, and an international organization, the UNHCR, states have committed to mutually admit onto their territory individuals fleeing conflict and persecution.
But today, this system is failing.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek asylum.
In practice, our immigration policies block the path to safety.
In theory, refugees have the right to integration or return to their country of origin.
But in practice, they remain trapped in eternal limbo.
In theory, refugees are a shared global responsibility.
In practice, geography dictates that countries close to the conflict host the overwhelming majority of refugees.
The system isn't broken because the rules are bad
but because we do not apply them adequately to a changing world, and that is what we must reconsider.
