But why are such journeys necessary in the era of low-cost airlines and modern consular means?
These journeys are not necessary and, last year, they led to the death of over 3,000 people at the borders of Europe and on European territory.
If refugees had the right to travel directly and apply for asylum in Europe, we would avoid this. And we can achieve this through humanitarian visas that allow individuals to obtain a visa from an embassy or consulate in a neighboring country and then pay for their ferry or plane ride to Europe.
It costs around 1,000 € to pay a smuggler from Turkey to the Greek islands.
A low-cost flight from Bodrum to Frankfurt costs 200 €.
If we allowed refugees, it would have major benefits.
This would save lives, it would diminish the market for smugglers, and it would mark the end of the disorder observed on the front lines of European entry points, such as the Greek islands.
It is the laws that prevent us from doing so, not a rational solution.
This is an idea that has been implemented.
Brazil has adopted a forward-thinking approach, with over 2,000 Syrians obtaining humanitarian visas, traveling to Brazil, and upon arrival, applying for refugee status.
In this setup, every Syrian who did this was granted refugee status and recognized as a refugee.
There is a historical precedent.
Between 1922 and 1942, these Nansen passports were used as travel documents allowing 450,000 Assyrians, Turks, and Chechens to travel to Europe and apply for refugee status elsewhere in Europe.
And the Nansen International Office for Refugees received the Nobel Peace Prize in recognition of this viable strategy.
Each of these four ideas that I have presented to you are ways to expand Amira's choices.
These are means by which we can increase the choices for refugees beyond these options, these three impossible options that I have detailed, while benefiting others as well.
In conclusion, we need a new perspective, a vision that expands the choices for refugees but acknowledges that they do not have to be a burden.
There is nothing inevitable about refugees being a cost.
Yes, they are a humanitarian responsibility, but they are human beings with skills, talents, aspirations, and the ability to contribute, if we allow them to.
In the new world, migration will not stop.
What we have seen in Europe will continue for years.
People will still travel, populations will be displaced, and we must find rational and realistic ways to manage this, not based on outdated logics of humanitarian aid and charity, but built on the opportunities offered by globalization, markets, and mobility.
I urge you to wake up and I urge our politicians to wake up to this challenge.
